1. Introduction¶

As avid NBA fans, our group has watched many regular season games over the past few years. During these games, we have noticed that announcers and fans have talked a lot about the evolution of the game. Head coaches, fans, and scouts alike have begun to rely a lot on statistics to make judgements about specific players. Also, in recent years, the game itself has evolved into a “positionless” game, meaning that each player must be versatile enough to fulfill the duties typically associated with each of the different basketball positions.

Thus, the question our group is investigating is:

How are the game statistics of a player indicative of the role that they play on the team?

Point Guard: Mostly responsible for passing and setting up plays, typically is the shortest player as well (we will see if this is true). Shooting Guard: Specialize in both scoring points and stealing the ball from opponents while playing defense. Small Forward: Considered the most versatile player. Often playing both offense and defense. Power Forward: Needs to be capable of rebounding and mid range shooting Center: Almost always the tallest player on the team. Plays similar to Power Forward, however are usually less mobile due to being in the center

Additional reading from the NBA: https://jr.nba.com/basketball-positions/

The first step in our process was to find data related to NBA players, their roles, and their game statistics. Luckily, Kaggle had a plethora of datasets to choose from with the exact data that we needed. We chose to use the 2023-2024 NBA Player Stats.

and obtained the file:

regular_season_2023-24.csv: This database contains 735 rows and 30 columns that contain information such as player id, name, position, age, team, and game statistics.

To clean up the data, we converted the data to the appropriate types, and checked for null values. The data didn’t contain null values, but it did contain multiple rows for the same player, in cases where players played for multiple teams in the same season. In these cases, players had TOT (total) for their cumulative stats. We decided to keep these stats for these players rather than keeping the data from the stints with each of the teams.

Convert string data into necessary numerical data

In [440]:
# Convert necessary columns from strings to integers
cols_to_convert_int = ["Rk", "Age", "G", "GS"]
for col in cols_to_convert_int:
    player_info_df[col] = player_info_df[col].apply(lambda x: int(x))


# Convert necessary columns from strings to floating point numbers
cols_to_convert_float = ["MP", "FG", "FGA", "FG%", "3P", "3PA", "3P%", "2P", "2PA", "2P%", "eFG%", "FT", "FTA", "FT%", "ORB", "DRB", "TRB", "AST", "STL", "BLK", "TOV", "PF", "PTS"]
for col in cols_to_convert_float:
    player_info_df[col] = player_info_df[col].apply(lambda x: float(x))

Our data has duplicate entries for players that were on different teams, where each entry corresponds to the data on their time with each team. Every player with duplicate entries also has an entry with TOT as the team name, representing the aggregated data from their time with each team. Since we're only concerned with individual player performance, we can drop the duplicate entries for players, and only keep the aggregate data.

Let's see if there's any correlation between Steals, Blocks, and Personal Fouls

As we can see, there are no linear correlations between the different series. However, while there isn't a particularly strong positive linear correlation between blocks and steals, steals and blocks both individually have fairly strong positive linear correlations with Personal Fouls, which makes sense, as those who attempt more steals and blocks must come in closer contact with other players, meaning they will be more likely to foul someone.

Statistical Method 2: Observing Distribution for Outliers¶

Let's examine if there are any outliers in average total rebounds per game for players by examining the distribution in a box plot

In [445]:
df = player_info_df
Q1 = df['TRB'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['TRB'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

outliers = df[(df['TRB'] < lower) | (df['TRB'] > upper)]
num_outliers = outliers.shape[0]
print(f"Number of Outliers: {num_outliers}")

Number of Outliers: 27

Looking at the distribution for average total rebounds per game we see that most of the values fall between 0 and 8 with a median of around 3 average total rebounds per game. However, there are many outliers in this dataset where certain individuals get much higher total rebounds per game compared to the median. This is likely due to multiple factors such as average playtime per game as players who are on the court more have more opportunities to get rebounds or height of the players as taller individuals have an advantage over others in getting the rebound after a shot.

Statistical Method 3: ANOVA Test¶

We want to know if specific basketball positions have an effect on the mean points per game. Since there are 5 groups of positions, we use an ANOVA test. Since some players played on different positions on different teams, we added the data for those players to the categories of each position they played for

For more on ANOVA tests read here: https://datatab.net/tutorial/anova

Null hypothesis: The position of a player has no effect on the mean points per game during the 2023-2024 regular season.
Alternative hypothesis: The position of a player affects the mean points per game during the 2023-2024 regular season.

In [446]:
grouped = player_info_df.groupby('Pos')
dfs = {name: group for name, group in grouped}

position_data = defaultdict(list)

for name, group in grouped:
    positions = name.split('-')

    for position in positions:
        position_data[position].append(group['PTS'].dropna().to_numpy())

Perform the Anova Test

In [448]:
anova_result = stats.f_oneway(*merged_positions_data.values())

print(f"P-value: {anova_result.pvalue}")

P-value: 0.34466212423934145

The P-value of 0.34466212423934145 is significantly higher than the standard significance level of 0.05. Given the P-value, we see that assuming the null hypothesis is true, the given data is very likely. Additionally, the P-value is greater than alpha, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is no significant difference between the mean points per game of players in each specific position (PG, SG, SF, PF, C).

4. Primary Analysis¶

We want to apply machine learning to the problem at hand of determining whether certain game statistics are indicative of a player role. There are many machine learning techniques to choose from so deciding which one would best fit our needs is crucial. Our question relates to game statistics indicating a specific player role meaning that we want our model to take in game statistics data and give us a prediction of what role it likely corresponds to. This is clearly a classification problem.

However, there are multiple classification models out there we aren’t sure which one might best fit our needs. Therefore, we decided to create multiple models and use k-fold cross validation in order to determine which classification model would be best for us to use.

Now That we've done our preprocessing, let's create our model! We want to see if we can correctly predict a player's position based on their game stats, to see if there is a significant relationship between the two. This looks like a job for a classification model, but which one do we choose?

In [458]:
k_folds = 5

for model_name, model in models.items():
    np.random.seed(seed)
    scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train_scaled, y_train, cv=skf)

5. Visualization¶

Let's plot the importances of each feature that our random forest classifier found.

In [461]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
importances = model.feature_importances_
indices = pd.Series(importances, index=X.columns).sort_values(ascending=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
indices.plot(kind="bar", color="skyblue")
plt.title("Feature Importance")
plt.ylabel("Importance Score")
plt.xlabel("Features")
plt.show()

Let's look at our decision trees in the random forest

In [462]:
from sklearn.tree import plot_tree

plt.figure(figsize=(24, 16))
plot_tree(tree, feature_names=X.columns, class_names = ['C', 'PF', 'SG', 'SF', 'PG'], filled=True)

For our classification task, we decided on using the random forest model because our k-fold cross validation found that it had the highest accuracy of commonly used models (~64% accuracy). After training our random forest model, we found that the most important features for determining the position of a player were assists, 3 point attempts, and offensive rebounds. We plotted each of these features by importance on a bar graph.

After creating a bar graph, we also wanted to experiment with displaying the decision trees involved with a random forest. The tree we plotted was quite complicated and difficult to read, but it shows that we used a lot of different features in determining player position. Also, classification tasks often create large decision trees when there are multiple different categories (in our case each of the 5 positions).

6. Insights and Conclusions¶

The classification of player roles based on game statistics is more complicated than we originally thought. Although the accuracy of our model wasn’t very high, we were still able to identify the most important/contributing features to the model’s decision making. The top three features were: Assists, 3 Point Attempts, and Offensive Rebounds.

Our data has shown that there are certain correlations between specific game stats and the position that a player plays. Through our exploratory analysis we found that there wasn’t much of a correlation between the role of a player and their points per game, which implies there may be other factors that determine whether or not a player is a good fit for a certain role.

We applied machine learning to find a relationship between the game statistics and player role so that it could be used as a classifier for future targets. This could be used to identify potential role changes for players who have specific game statistics that might be better suited to a role other than the one they currently play. This could also help to identify weaknesses and strengths of players as well as help coaches identify various possible lineups for their team.

Using the Random Forest Model, we were able to find those relationships between game statistics and player roles. While this predictor is not entirely accurate and is not an absolute indicator of role suitability for players, this could be one point that coaches consider when looking at players and their overall team composition.
